<subSubSection id="F0DE654CFFB9671600A42134FD8EFA75" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B87B36C7FFB9671600A42134FAE3FA2E" blockId="13.[151,1436,1039,1663]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB9671600A42134FDEFFB98" bold="true" box="[151,578,1039,1065]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Generic diagnosis. Adult female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="20FF2A42FFB967160266212BFD0EFB9B" box="[597,675,1040,1066]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="14.[151,259,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[242,1366,309,1877]" captionTargetId="figure-118@14.[209,1384,309,1888]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 5. Apiococcus gregarius Hempel. Adult female, where A = variously-shaped dorsal setae; B = dorsal microtubular duct; C = dorsal loculate pore; D = area of derm showing position of microtubular ducts and loculate pores; F = view of anal area, showing position of inner pouches; J = ventral setae; L = ventral loculate pore; P = spiracle; V = antenna, and X = anal pouch with sunken loculate pores." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5313342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5313342/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Globular; derm entirely membranous. 
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB967160492212BFAAEFB98" box="[1185,1283,1040,1065]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Dorsum</emphasis>
. Derm with areolations. Setae of 
<specimenCount id="AEC2FD4EFFB9671601BC210EFE45FBFE" box="[399,488,1077,1103]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="generic" typeStatus="types">2 types</specimenCount>
: large, roundly conical setae in segmental rows, and narrower setae on posterior abdominal segments. Macrotubular ducts absent. Microtubular ducts appearing bilocular, frequent throughout. Loculate pores each with mainly 5 loculi, present in bands across posterior abdominal segments and in a large group on head. Anal lobes barely developed, each with a group of setae; also with an elongate invagination or pouch with internal loculate pores possibly associated with each anal lobe; median plate absent. Anal ring apparently represented by a membranous opening. 
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB96716038B21CBFBBBFAB8" box="[952,1046,1264,1289]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Margin.</emphasis>
Not defined. 
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB96716048621CBFB53FAB8" box="[1205,1278,1264,1289]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Venter</emphasis>
. More lateral setae as on dorsum but other setae rather hairlike. Macrotubular ducts absent. Microtubular ducts as on dorsum, throughout but sparse in places. Loculate pores similar to those on dorsum, in bands across abdomen and less frequent elsewhere. Cruciform pores absent. Antennae 1 segmented. Frontal lobes and antennal tubercles absent. Labium with unknown number of segments. Legs entirely absent. Vulva not detected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B87B36C7FFB9671600F52091FD8EFA75" blockId="13.[151,1436,1039,1663]" box="[198,547,1450,1476]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Known only from 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FFB9671601AC2091FDB2FA75" box="[415,543,1450,1476]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Myrtaceae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F0DE654CFFB9671600F520F4FC09F9CE" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B87B36C7FFB9671600F520F4FC09F9CE" blockId="13.[151,1436,1039,1663]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB9671600F520F4FEE4FA58" bold="true" box="[198,329,1487,1513]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Comment.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FFB96716016420EBFE73FA58" box="[343,478,1488,1513]" class="Chlorophyceae" family="Gloeodendraceae" genus="Apiococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Tetrasporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB96716016420EBFE73FA58" box="[343,478,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Apiococcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
currently contains 4 species (
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FFB96716036820EBFBCFFA5B" authority="Hempel" authorityName="Hempel" authorityYear="1900" box="[859,1122,1488,1514]" class="Chlorophyceae" family="Gloeodendraceae" genus="Apiococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Tetrasporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="asperatus">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB96716036820EBFC59FA58" box="[859,1012,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">A. asperatus</emphasis>
Hempel
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FFB96716044720EBFADDFA5B" authority="Hempel" authorityName="Hempel" authorityYear="1900" box="[1140,1392,1488,1514]" class="Chlorophyceae" family="Gloeodendraceae" genus="Apiococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Tetrasporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="globosus">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB96716044720EBFAAEFA58" box="[1140,1283,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">A. globosus</emphasis>
Hempel
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FFB9671605B020EBFEA5F9BF" class="Chlorophyceae" family="Gloeodendraceae" genus="Apiococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Tetrasporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="gregarius">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB9671605B020EBFEA5F9BF" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">A. gregarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FFB96716017A20CEFDEAF9BE" authority="Hempel" authorityName="Hempel" box="[329,583,1525,1551]" class="Chlorophyceae" family="Gloeodendraceae" genus="Apiococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Tetrasporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB96716017A20CEFE4DF9BF" box="[329,480,1525,1550]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">A. singularis</emphasis>
Hempel
</taxonomicName>
) all currently known only from 
<collectingCountry id="C0D37657FFB9671603F120CEFBA0F9BE" box="[962,1037,1525,1551]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. We have examined specimens of all but 
<emphasis id="8AB0EAD5FFB9671600DF2320FDBCF985" box="[236,529,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FFB9671600DF2320FED1F985" authorityName="Hempel" authorityYear="1900" box="[236,380,1563,1588]" class="Chlorophyceae" family="Gloeodendraceae" genus="Apiococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Tetrasporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="globosus">A. globosus</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="7FC44D44FFB9671601BB2320FDBCF985" box="[392,529,1563,1588]" class="Chlorophyceae" family="Gloeodendraceae" genus="Apiococcus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Tetrasporales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="genus">Apiococcus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differs from all other eriococcid genera in having 2 elongate invaginations near the anal area which contain many loculate pores. It also is rotund, has distinctively cupolate-shaped setae, lacks legs, has 1-segmented antennae, and forms a test on the host.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
